<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-955-494  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 955 494.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>M.D. Computing  Sept-Oct 1989 v6 n5 p290(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The Micro Corner. (medical clinic heuristics become computerized)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bergeron, Bryan; Locke, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The need of physicians to assemble clinical heuristics fromdiverse sources is being helped by ever more powerful softwaretools, exemplified by the U/A Doctor and the CAP Project softwarepackages reviewed in related articles.andP;  It is difficult for adoctor to remember all phenomena associated with a specificmedical condition, so lists are used of diseases and theirassociated signs and symptoms, and heuristic rules are used tofacilitate diagnosis.andP;  Computers are a natural environment forsuch clinical algorithms, and a growing number of diagnosticsupport programs have been developed.andP;  Some are authoring toolsthat enable doctors to assemble their own algorithms from theirown and other's clinical experience and rules.andP;  Some programs,such as U/A Doctor, are finished products, with algorithmstargeted at specific diagnostic problems.andP;  Future programs willintegrate both capabilities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Diagnostic AssessmentSoftware PackagesMedical DiagnosisClinical MedicineAutomationMicrocomputersApplicationsAlgorithm AnalysisSoftware Design.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>